stories.text:
Sorry if already old news, but I just got my twitter blocked permanently and that makes me feel weird. This seemed to make sense when it happened to others as I thought Trump had it coming, but blocking my account doesn't make sense at all.

I have at most 5 re-tweets ever and possibly 2 comments. Last activity was more than a year ago.

I just looked at their rules and I couldn't have broke any of the Safety ones neither the ones from Privacy.

The only rules I see as subjective enough to possibly explain a blocking of my account would be the ones from Authenticity. But then again, I didn't create content on the platform, I only re-shared it. Does that mean that all the users that re-shared with similar patterns got banned (from what I remember, the users I re-tweeted had a high number of followers)?

I guess punishing at random, on a permanent timeline and without any previous notice is an easy way to change views. I do see now the sense behind the whole movement against cancellation policy.
